<TITLE> Kuwait MPs to put more ministers under pressure </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KUWAIT, Oct 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Islamist members of Kuwait's parliament petitioned on Monday to question two ministers after reported mistakes, political sources said, putting more pressure on a government struggling to implement economic reforms. Kuwait, a major OPEC oil producer, already has three vacant ministerial portfolios including the key post of oil minister, empty since Sheikh Ali al-Jarrah al-Sabah left in June to avert a no-confidence vote in parliament. The petition request will now put pressure on the finance and justice ministers. In the past, the government has averted such grillings by reshuffling the cabinet. Islamist MP Dhaifallah Buramia submitted a request to question Finance Minister Badr al-Humaidhi after a newspaper suggested that he had made administrative and financial mistakes, the sources said. Two other Islamist MPs submitted a request to question Justice, Endowments and Islamic Affairs Minister Abdallah al-Matuq, after the same newspaper suggested he had made mistakes that violated the constitution. It was not immediately possible to contact the ministers. It has been only a few months since the latest reshuffle. Since then, Sherida al-Moasherji has stepped down as communications minister and the new health minister, Massouma al-Mubarak, also quit, after a hospital fire in August. Kuwait's parliament has a history of challenging the government in a region where ruling families keep a tight grip on politics. The cabinet has made little progress in securing the approval of parliament for a series of economic reforms. As political parties are banned, there is often a lack of coordination among deputies flooding the floor with motions and sometimes pursuing personal agendas. Kuwait's ruler, Emir Sheikh Sabah al-Ahmad al-Sabah, who has the last say in politics, has repeatedly urged deputies and the government to work together. Analysts say he was on the brink earlier this year of dissolving parliament due to the deadlock. The house 